ueerness, at first latent, became a vibrant yet continually conflicted part of the family-sitcom tradition. Taking into account elements such as the casting of child actors, the use of and experimentation with plot traditions, the contradictory interpretive valences of comedy, and the subtle subversions of moral standards by writers and directors, Pugh points out how innocence and sexuality conflict on television. As older sitcoms often sit on a pedestal of nostalgia as representative of the Golden Age of the American Family, television history reveals a deeper, queerer vision of family bonds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHomosexuality and television. 0aHomosexuality on television. 0aSex role on television. 0aSituation comedies (Television programs)zUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aTelevision programsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican family.  aAmerican sitcom.  achild actor.  acomedy.  afamily sitcom.  algbtq.  aqueer.  asexuality.  asitcom.  atelevision.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066608340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813591759zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813591759zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813591759.jpg  a978-3-11-066608-3 Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA